  "prompt": "Why is a tooth extracted after a root canal?",
  "response": "A tooth is typically not extracted after a root canal. In fact, the purpose of a root canal is to save a tooth that might otherwise need to be extracted. Here's a clarification:\n\n1. Root canal treatment:\n- Removes infected or damaged pulp from inside the tooth\n- Cleans and disinfects the root canal\n- Fills and seals the tooth to prevent further infection\n- Allows the tooth to remain in place and continue functioning\n\n2. Reasons a tooth might be extracted after a root canal:\n- The tooth is too damaged or weakened to be saved\n- The root canal treatment was unsuccessful\n- Severe infection that cannot be treated\n- Extensive decay or structural damage\n- Tooth cannot be properly restored\n- Complex root structure preventing effective treatment\n\n3. Post-root canal care:\n- Usually, a crown is placed to protect and strengthen the tooth\n- Most teeth can remain functional after root canal treatment\n\nIn summary, extraction is not a standard outcome of root canal treatment. The goal is to preserve the natural tooth whenever possible. Extraction is only considered if the tooth cannot be successfully treated or restored.",
